In synchronous programming, also known as wait-for-it programming or event-driven programming, all code is executed sequentially in a single thread. This means that when one function completes its execution, control passes to the next function until the entire program has finished running. On the other hand, asynchronous programming allows for non-blocking I/O and network operations, which means that the browser will continue to process other events while awaiting long or heavy tasks like API calls or file downloads.

Here's an example of synchronous code in JavaScript:

```javascript
function printNumbers() {
  for (let i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    console.log(i);
  }
}
printNumbers(); // This will wait for the function to complete before moving on to the next line of code.
```

